<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910131-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>910131-0023.</DOCID><HL>   Brady Seeks to Coordinate   Bid to Boost Bank Lending</HL><DATE>01/31/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7</SO><IN>BANKS (BNK)</IN><GV>TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady haslaunched an effort to coordinate regulatory initiativesdesigned to encourage bank lending and to ease the creditcrunch.   Mr. Brady appointed Deputy Secretary John Robson to headinteragency efforts to study a number of accounting and otherchanges that could free up more money for lending. Officialsfrom the Federal Reserve Board, the Federal Deposit InsuranceCorp., the Comptroller of the Currency and the Office ofThrift Supervision met with Mr. Robson yesterday.</LP><TEXT>   A senior Treasury official said the group will focus onquestions such as asset valuation that could influence theamount of reserves banks have to set aside to offsetnonperforming loans and possibly increase bank profits andcapital in an effort to spur lending. The group will alsolook for ways to encourage banks to work with troubledborrowers trying to weather hard times.   In recent months, the Federal Reserve has lowered interestrates in an effort to spur economic growth, but the easingalone hasn't been enough to help New England and other areashard hit by falling real estate prices.</TEXT></DOC>